un, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bordeaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aldea, Andre, Andree, Clovis, Jean Claude, Jean-Luc, Leonce.","French:","habitational name from the city of Bordeaux in Gironde, the Latin name of which is <i>Burdigala</i>, of unexplained etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Bordeau","meanings":["French: topographic name, a derivative of   Borde   ‘hut, smallholding, small farm’. It may also be a habitational name from any of the places called Bordeau.","Altered form of French   Bourdeau  , a variant of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pierre IV de Bordeaux was born about 1190. He had at least 1 daughter with Assalide de Rancon. He died in 1274, at the age of 85."},"et":{"environ 1190–1274":"umbes 1190–1274","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1237–1281":"1237–1281","1190–1274":"1190–1274","1190":"1190","1237":"1237","1210":"1210","1274":"1274","environ 1190":"umbes 1190","1281":"1281","Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1190–1274":"noin 1190–1274","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1237–1281":"1237–1281","1190–1274":"1190–1274","1190":"1190","1237":"1237","1210":"1210","1274":"1274","environ 1190":"noin 1190","1281":"1281","Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, Ranska"},"fr":{"environ 1190–1274":"environ 1190–1274","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1237–1281":"1237–1281","1190–1274":"1190–1274","1190":"1190","1237":"1237","1210":"1210","1274":"1274","environ 1190":"environ 1190","1281":"1281","Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, France":"Bordeaux, Gironde, Aquitaine, France"